Background Information:

Cetaceans, whales and dolphins, inhabit inshore and offshore waters of New Jersey. A stranding is defined as an event that occurs in the wild when a marine mammal is found dead on the shore or floating along the shore in United States coastal waters. Strandings occur as a single stranding that involves one individual or a mass stranding that involves many animals due to disease, human interaction or other unknown factors. Data was obtained from the North East division of the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) for all marine mammal strandings in the states of New Jersey and Delaware from January 2000-October 2017. Marine mammals are federally protected species under the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972. Data was collected using Level A stranding reports with trained professionals of the Marine Mammal Stranding Center in New Jersey and the MERR Institute in Delaware. Stranding data provides important details to understand the morphology, life history, biology, and general health of marine mammals. It may also detect environmental threats and negative human impacts that may have conservation implications.

National Marine Fisheries Service, Department of Commerce (2017). Marine Mammal Health and Stranding Response Database [2000-2017_StrandingData.csv].

Read in data using R:

Our data is stored as a .csv file. A comma separated value (.csv) file uses commas to separate values. There are no formulas, formatting, comments, etc., in a csv file. If you save an Excel file as a CSV file, the formulas, formatting and comments in your file will disappear to just represent the values. We need to read the CSV file into R as a data frame to be able to work with it.
In order to read in your .csv file of data into R, it needs to be found within the same folder you have this document saved. If that is not the case, you will need to set your working directory:

# Get your working directory. Your working directory is the path to this file. This may look different for PC users/Mac users.
getwd()

If the above path is not where you have your .csv data file saved, you will need to set your working directory. To obtain the path for where your file is located:

Mac: Right click on the folder -> Get Info -> Copy as path name:

Windows: Double click on the path bar and it will reformat to copy and paste:

Read in the data using read.csv()

# Read in the data from the .csv file:
# Use TAB to auto complete
# "file name", - Case and space sensitive!
# header = TRUE - because our data has headers (Column names)
stranding <- read.csv("2000-2017_StrandingData.csv", header = TRUE)
The variable “stranding” has 2500 rows and 33 columns of data as seen in your R environment.

We can also get this same information by checking the dimensions of our data:

dim(stranding)
[1] 2500   33

Our data has 2500 rows and 33 columns.

Summarizing your data will give you different results based on the data types within your columns. For example, numerical data types will give you the minimum, maximum, and median of your vector. Character columns are text columns. For large data sets, you can view the first few rows by using the head() function:

# View only the first 6 rows of data
head(stranding)

List the column names of your data:

When exploring data, it is important to take the time to UNDERSTAND the data as well. A lot of this information can be found in the metadata. Metadata is data about the data. How was the data collected? What data collection procedures are important to know when trying to answer questions about your data? What are the units of a column? Are columns measured as categorical values or numerical values? The Level A stranding data sheet has about 60 columns of data per animal stranding, but when I made this data request, I only requested the 33 listed below. The stranding data sheet has the answers to some of the example questions stated above.

Explore your data using libraries:

There are many different libraries that are useful for working with your data. Many of these work together with each other and the base R functions.

tidyverse - A collection of packages to explore and manipulate your data

  • dplyr - Manipulating your data by filtering and rearranging

  • lubridate - Working with dates and times in your data

  • readr - Importing data in multiple different formats

  • ggplot2 - Basic graphs for data visualisation

Installing a package into R:

#install.packages("tidyverse")

You can select a specific column within the stranding data frame by specifying the column name, Species. Note that we are not saving a new data frame as a variable to use later, we are just viewing it at this time.

select(stranding, Species)

Now let’s say we want to look at all of the times a specific species was observed stranded. We can filter for the Bottlenose dolphin, or Tursiops truncatus, by specifying to filter for truncatus. The genus name is Tursiops and the species name is truncatus. This data set specifies a specific species by indicating just the species name.

We can select for Bottlenose dolphins by using the operator ==, specifying for truncatus. It will now only show us entries when Bottlenose dolphins stranded.

# Use filter to select for a specific species, truncatus, within the column Species
filter(stranding, Species == "truncatus")

What if we did not have our data as a CSV file? We can read Excel files too, and there are many library options for multiple different file formats. Let’s install readxl as recommended by R for Data Science.

# Install package readxl as recommended by R for Data Science
# https://r4ds.hadley.nz/spreadsheets
# install.packages("readxl")

#Load the package
library(readxl)

#Load the data
stranding_excel <- read_xls("2000-2017_StrandingData.xls",col_names = TRUE)
The new variable “stranding_excel” has 2500 rows and 33 columns of data as seen in your R environment just like our original variable. The library readxl can also be used to read in .csv files using function read_csv()

  • Logical: Boolean values (TRUE or FALSE)

Vectors and Factors

Vectors are manually specified using c(). We can input our data to create a vector from scratch using c().

?c()

# Manually create a vector of professor last names:
professors <- c("Baldwin", "Dunn", "Laurino", "Olsen", "Sokol", "Trout")

professors
[1] "Baldwin" "Dunn"    "Laurino" "Olsen"   "Sokol"   "Trout"
We can now see the vector under Values in our environment.

Since we already have our data, we can use our Species column. The Species column is shown as a Character column, but we can convert this column to a Factor instead. Factors are special vectors that store the data as categorical values, which is what we have in the Species column.

Before we get started, we can remove the vector we just created.

rm(professors)

professors is now no longer under Values in our environment.

# Create a vector from the Species column:
species_vector <- stranding$Species
# If we print the vector, you'll see a vector of the Species column, similar to what we saw with the professor vector.
# species_vector

# Convert the vector to a factor using factor()
species_factor <- factor(species_vector)

We have two options here, we can replace the current Species column within the stranding data frame as a factor, OR we can create a new column in the data frame. The benefits of creating a new column is preserving the original data. Creating a new column allows us to group this data for potential graphing or looking at the counts of species that have stranded.

# Add the factor as a NEW column in the data frame, stranding:
stranding$Species_factor <- species_factor

We added a new column to our data frame, now displaying 34 variables within our environment, but we did not write the changes to the .csv file at this time. If you open your .csv file in Excel, you will not see an additional column. We just created a new column in our R data frame at this time.

Now displaying 34 variables instead of 33.
str(stranding$Species_factor)
 Factor w/ 34 levels "","acutorostrata",..: 22 32 14 21 14 32 32 29 22 29 ...

We have successfully added a new column to our data as a factor instead of character values.

Lists

Lists can hold different sizes and types of data such as characters, vectors, factors, integers, additional lists, etc. at the same time.

# Summary statistics for the Latitude column
latitude_summary <- summary(stranding$ConversionLAT)

# Summary statistics for the Longitude column
longitude_summary <- summary(stranding$ConversionLONG)

# Create a list() with the above values, plus the species factor we created before:
stranding_list <- list(species_factor, latitude_summary, longitude_summary)

# Print the list
stranding_list

Now we have a list of different data from our data frame.

# Assign names to our new list of data
names(stranding_list) <- c("Species Stranded", "Latitude Summary", "Longitude Summary")

# View the list
print(stranding_list)

With this specific data set, we would not need this list, but maybe we could find a use for it :) If we had multiple different data frames, we could pull data from separate data frames to create a unique list.

Matrices

Matrices can only hold the same types of data, such as integers. We can manually create a 2x6 matrix of the summary statistics of the latitude and longitude we obtained earlier.

# Manually create a matrix using the values from the summary of the latitudes and longitudes:
matrix <- matrix(c(36.77, 39.02, 39.41, 39.50, 39.98, 53.86, -80.23, -74.85, -74.37,  -74.48, -74.07, -72.32), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE)

# View the matrix
matrix

[1,]  36.77  39.02  39.41  39.50  39.98  53.86
[2,] -80.23 -74.85 -74.37 -74.48 -74.07 -72.32

Name the rows of your matrix:

# Name the rows of the matrix
rownames(matrix) <- c("Latitude", "Longitude")

# Name the columns of the matrix
colnames(matrix) <- c("Min", "1st Qu.", "Median", "Mean", "3rd Qu.", "Max")

Dates and Times

Check the structure of the date column, ObservationDate, in our stranding data frame using base R:

str(stranding$ObservationDate)
 chr [1:2500] "2008-MAR-14" "2004-SEP-23" "2008-APR-26" "2008-MAR-02" "2008-APR-26" "2007-JUL-01" "2007-AUG-20" ...

We have to specify the custom date format we want our dates read as. We can use "%Y-%b-%d" since:

  • %Y is for the 4-digit year (2008)

  • %b is for the abbreviated month name (“MAR”). We have to specify this as an abbreviated month.

  • %d is for the day of the month (14)

The dates are being read as characters. Change the format of this column to be read as dates using base R:

# Specify the format of the date column. We can see from the structure above, it is written in Year-Abbreviated Month-Day
stranding$ObservationDate <- as.Date(stranding$ObservationDate, format = "%Y-%b-%d")

# Check the structure again to confirm the change
str(stranding$ObservationDate)
 Date[1:2500], format: "2008-03-14" "2004-09-23" "2008-04-26" "2008-03-02" "2008-04-26" "2007-07-01" "2007-08-20" "2007-04-25" "2007-04-30" ...

All data is different and there are many different types of ways the date may be recorded in your data. Here are additional examples with the correct R format to specify:

Date Format Data Example R Format
Year-Month-Day 2008-03-14 %Y-%m-%d
Day-Month-Year 14-03-2008 %d-%m-%Y
Month-Day-Year 03/14/2008 %m/%d/%Y
Abbreivated Month-Day-Year Mar 14, 2008 %b %d, %Y
Day-Month-Year 14 March 2008 %d %B %Y
Day-Abbreviated Month-Year 14-Mar-2008 %d-%b-%Y
Year/Month/Day 2008/03/14 %Y/%m/%d

Some data sets may also include the date and time in the same column. You can separate columns that have the date and time together, or you can tell R what you are working with:

Date and Time Format (Same Column) Data Example R Format
Year-Month-Day Hour 2008-03-14 14:45 %Y-%m-%d %H:%M
Year-Month-Day Hour:Minute 2008-03-14 14:45:33 %Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S
Hour with AM/PM 02:45 PM %I:%M %p
Time with Time Zone 14:45:33 UTC %H:%M:%S %Z

The I% stands for the 12 hour clock system (Not the 24hr clock).

The p% stands for AM or PM and is used with the I% above.

The %Z stands for the time zone abbreviation.

Our stranding data frame does not have time. The final stranding report will include the time the necropsy was completed and an estimated time of death for the animal from the level of decomposition.
